1. Select Your Currency
USD is the default. 

2. Know the Niá¹£Äb

The niá¹£Äb is the minimum liable amount that a Muslim must have to be obligated to pay Zakat. This amount was set by our Prophet Muhammad (S) at 21 ounces of Silver. Based on today's price of Silver per ounce, the niá¹£Äb is (current price of silver * 21). We will automatically let you know if you're under the niá¹£Äb amount. Note: we will not be using the gold nisab calculation in this calculator to stay true to Sheikh Joe Bradford's method.

3. Understand the Hawl

The hawl is the the Zakat Year, like a fiscal year, but used to calculate your Zakat. The hawl starts when your assets first reached the minimum niá¹£Äb, or when you last paid Zakat. Once 1 lunar year has passed, and your assets have been consistently above the niá¹£Äb, you pay Zakat on your assets at that point.

4. You, Your Spouse, & Children

Zakat is due by any person who owns the wealth, whether man, woman, or child if they possess above the nisab. If you choose, you can pay Zakat on behalf of your family, in which case, make sure to sum the total for each individual in the following questions.


Let's get started with the assets that you will be paying Zakat on first. Later, we will cover debts and payments that may reduce your Zakatable amount.

